.TH "drm_mm_scan_init_with_range" 9 "drm_mm_scan_init_with_range" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
drm_mm_scan_init_with_range \- initialize range-restricted lru scanning
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "void" drm_mm_scan_init_with_range
.BI "(struct drm_mm_scan *scan "  ","
.BI "struct drm_mm *mm "  ","
.BI "u64 size "  ","
.BI "u64 alignment "  ","
.BI "unsigned long color "  ","
.BI "u64 start "  ","
.BI "u64 end "  ","
.BI "enum drm_mm_insert_mode mode "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "scan" 12
scan state
.IP "mm" 12
drm_mm to scan
.IP "size" 12
size of the allocation
.IP "alignment" 12
alignment of the allocation
.IP "color" 12
opaque tag value to use for the allocation
.IP "start" 12
start of the allowed range for the allocation
.IP "end" 12
end of the allowed range for the allocation
.IP "mode" 12
fine-tune the allocation search and placement
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This simply sets up the scanning routines with the parameters for the desired
hole.

Warning:
As long as the scan list is non-empty, no other operations than
adding/removing nodes to/from the scan list are allowed.
